While I suppose it is technically possible, it's a little bit unusual: such an iterator doesn't satisfy the [InputIterator concept](http://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/concept/InputIterator)--it requires both `==` and `!=` operators, which means such an iterator won't work with many stl functions that take an InputIterator, either.

I think we should officially require a proper InputIterator here.  But if we had that requirement, we actually could switch it (and fix the test code iterator) so that for-range compatible iterators would work (though unofficially without a promise not to break them in the future).  On the other hand, requiring full InputIterators doesn't seem like a huge burden on users, either.

@wjakob, @dean0x7d - thoughts?

@bmw Hmm a couple things:

1. In that case, what certbot-auto should do is error with a messaging informing the user of that requirement (--csr and certonly). I was actually using certonly, but the short text "with auth --csr" didn't hold any meaning to me, so I ignored it. If you put a message in the CLI, then you don't even need to mention that requirement in the docs - the cli will tell you. 

2. Why should you  need to pass the --csr option? I only want to control where the resulting certificate is saved, not control what signing request is used. It should be possible to specify where cerbot saves the cert even if you allow certbot to create new keys (and thus a new certificate signing request) for you.

